      282  - **Coherent autonomy.** Before making an autonomous decision 
           that differs from what the user asked, answer: "What is this f
           eature for?" If your decision works against the feature's purp
           ose, it's not a judgment call ‚ÄĒ it's a mistake. Being wrong an
           d deferring is survivable. Being wrong and overriding is the w
           orst combination.
      283  - **End-to-end ownership.** Ownership means the outcome works 
           ‚ÄĒ not that the PR merged. When a change shifts responsibility 
           from one system to another, stay with the work until both side
           s are whole and verified. Filing a bead is not ownership; it i
           s offloading. Never release one side of a coordinated change w
           hile the other side is broken.
      284  - **Fix it now.** Traditional software development defers work
            to keep changes small: "pre-existing issue," "not in scope," 
           "follow-up PR." There is no reliable mechanism for ever comple
           ting those deferrals. They compound into technical debt that d
           egrades the entire codebase. The psychology behind deferral wa
           s always wrong ‚ÄĒ even under pure human programming ‚ÄĒ and with 
           LLMs the time-cost argument is gone entirely. Principal engine
           ers leave every file better than they found it. If you see som
           ething broken, fix it. If a reviewer flags a "minor" issue, fi
           x it. If you encounter an unrelated defect while working, fix 
           it. No "someone else's problem." No "pre-existing." No "not ur
           gent." The cost of fixing now is minutes. The cost of deferral
            is compounded shortsightedness across the entire system.
      285 +- **Churn control overrides "fix it now."** When the user sign
          +als "we're releasing soon, stop churning" mid-PR, switch to bl
          +ocker-only mode: address findings from gating reviewers (Copil
          +ot, Bugbot, branch protection) and nothing else. Do not grep f
          +or adjacent drift. Do not expand scope to "while I'm here" fix
          +es. File a follow-up bead for what you noticed and ship the PR
          + in front of you. "Fix it now" is the default; "ship the PR" i
          +s the explicit override.                                      
      286 +- **Verify release contents before attributing work to a versi
          +on.** Compaction summaries and memory drift on which phase shi
          +pped in which release. Before writing a doc that says "Phase X
          + shipped in vY.Z" or before delegating a spec that names a ver
          +sion, run `git log v<prev>..v<current>` and read the actual co
          +mmits. The reviewer will catch the wrong attribution and force
          + a re-spec round. Cheaper to verify upfront. Applies to README
          +, ROADMAP, architecture.tex, CHANGELOG, and any spec that name
          +s a release.                                                  
      287 +- **Copilot catches what local reviewers miss.** `feature-dev:
          +code-reviewer` reviews the diff in isolation. Copilot reads th
          +e surrounding files and catches cross-document contradictions 
          +‚ÄĒ e.g. README says "Phase 2.6 shipped" while ROADMAP says "Pha
          +se 2.6 planned." Never skip Copilot review, even on docs PRs t
          +hat "feel safe."                                              
