‚ĚĮ What is the executive summary for what we have learned so far. What worked    
  what did not. Keep it 3-4 paragraphs in total and no jargon.                  
‚óŹ The delegation system works, and it works harder than I expected. We took it
  for a real test drive: a scripted dry run first, then a real code fix handed
  to a specialist agent through the same channel. Both succeeded, and the real
  fix is in a pull request now going through normal review.

  The first real job hit a problem I created ‚ÄĒ my instructions listed the files
  the worker could touch but missed an adjacent test file he needed to update.
  The worker noticed and stopped cold rather than silently reaching for the
  missing file, which is exactly the behavior we built the system to enforce. I
  had to formally cancel that job and reissue it with a corrected list. Writing
  complete instructions turns out to be harder than I assumed; tests and
  documentation that pair with a code file are an easy oversight. When the
  corrected second pass ran, it finished clean, and then the code reviewer (a
  separate agent) found a real bug in the tests ‚ÄĒ not in the fix itself, but in
  a check that would pass in our normal setup and quietly fail in containers
  with unusual time-zone settings. When I sent the reviewer's suggested patch
  back to the worker, the worker in turn noticed the reviewer's suggestion was
  still too narrow and landed a wider fix handling three edge cases I'd never
  have thought to enumerate. Every layer of the chain caught something the layer
   above missed. That's stronger quality than I expected from a dry run.

  Two rough edges worth flagging. First, the tool is silent when commands
  succeed ‚ÄĒ no confirmation, nothing you can chain against ‚ÄĒ so you have to run
  a second command to verify your last one landed. Small bug, I filed it.
  Second, there's no graceful way for a worker to say "I need more room to do
  this right" partway through a job; my worker had to use a workaround and flag
  it in notes. It worked, but it wasn't obvious how, and we should at least
  document the escape hatch. Everything else ‚ÄĒ the work instructions, the review
   checkpoints, the permanent record of who did what and when ‚ÄĒ behaved exactly
  as designed.

