‚ĚĮ How do we solve the clarification / escalation need?                          

‚óŹ The primitive already has an escalate path ‚ÄĒ it's just hidden, and the current
   schema semantically overloads it. Here's what I see:

  What already works

  A worker can submit a result with verdict: escalate, files_changed: [], and
  the blocker reason in open_questions + prose. The validator explicitly allows
  empty files_changed (see internal/mission/result.go lines 161‚Äď164: "may be
  empty only when the round made no file changes"). I used this path this
  afternoon to formalize bwk's round-1 escalation, and it closed cleanly with
  --status escalated. The event log records it.

  What's broken

  Discoverability. bwk didn't know this path existed until I told him. The ethos
   mission result --help example shows only a verdict: pass case with a
  non-empty files list. Nothing in the CLI help, the docs, or the delegation
  template hints that files_changed: [] is a legal shape or that open_questions
  is where a blocker goes. Every new worker will rediscover this the hard way.

  Semantic overloading. A verdict: escalate result currently covers two distinct
   cases: "I tried and couldn't finish the work" and "I couldn't start because
  the scope is wrong." They share a shape but mean different things. Future
  analytics or operator dashboards can't distinguish them without parsing prose.

  Two fixes, complementary, different cost

  Fix A ‚ÄĒ document the escape hatch (cheap, ship now). Update ethos mission 
  result --help to include an escalate example with empty files_changed,
  open_questions populated, and prose explaining the blocker. Add a one-sentence
   blurb to ethos mission --help that reads something like "If the contract's
  scope is wrong, submit an escalate result instead of trying to work around
  it." Update the leader delegation template I've been using so the escalate
  protocol is in every contract's context. Zero schema change. One small PR. A
  new worker will find this in the help before hitting the wall.

  Fix B ‚ÄĒ add a pre-delegation lint (higher value, more work). A new command:
  ethos mission lint <contract.yaml> that runs before create and surfaces
  heuristic warnings: "write_set contains foo.go but not foo_test.go",
  "write_set contains production files but no CHANGELOG.md entry", "success
  criteria mention README but README.md is not in write_set." Non-blocking,
  advisory only. It addresses the root cause ‚ÄĒ my spec-writing errors ‚ÄĒ rather
  than just routing them through a cleaner escalate channel. The gaps we hit in
  round 1 would all have been caught by trivial static checks at lint time.

  Fix A addresses the symptom; Fix B addresses the cause. Fix A is a few hours.
  Fix B is meaningfully more design work ‚ÄĒ what checks are worth running, what's
   a warning vs a block, how does the lint stay in sync with evolving
  conventions.

  My recommendation

  Do Fix A now, as the next bead after Phase 4.1 ships. File Fix B as a P2 bead
  with a design sketch, and schedule it when we have more dogfood evidence about
   which lint rules would have paid off. The reason to sequence it this way: Fix
   A is guaranteed value (documentation that definitely helps new workers),
  while Fix B's value depends on which lint rules we pick, and we only have one
  dogfood cycle of data to pick from. Two or three more dogfoods will tell us
  which rules are worth writing.

  The one thing I'd reject is adding a third artifact type (a dedicated Block or
   ScopeRequest shape alongside Result and Reflection). The current Result type
  already carries the data; adding a new shape is ceremony. The fix is telling
  people the shape is there, not adding another one to learn.

  Your call: ship Fix A as the next bead after the current PR lands, or sequence
   differently?

