‚ĚĮ Now give me an executive summary for the CEO level.                           

‚óŹ The delegation system works in production, and its layered review is already 
  catching quality issues I would have missed on my own. PR 199 is merged: the
  first real code fix delivered entirely through the new structured workflow. It
   took seven revisions driven by reviewer findings ‚ÄĒ every layer of review (the
   specialist worker, the local code reviewer, Copilot, and Bugbot) caught
  something the layer above it missed. That's stronger quality than I expected
  from a test drive; it's closer to what we hoped the system would eventually
  produce once it matured.

  The most valuable feedback came from the failure cases. The worker stopped
  cold when he hit a boundary I'd defined incorrectly, which forced me to
  formally cancel the first attempt and reissue a corrected version ‚ÄĒ exactly
  the behavior we designed in. Later, Bugbot caught a subtle test regression I'd
   introduced while fixing an earlier comment: my correction made the test pass
  for the wrong reason, so it would have accepted a completely broken version of
   the function without noticing. The system flagged it, and the worker proved
  his fix was real by temporarily breaking the function and watching the test
  now catch it. That level of rigor is what we want to be normal.

  The real-world run also surfaced seven rough edges in the delegation system
  itself, all now filed as tracked work items. The most important is that the
  tool is silent after every successful command ‚ÄĒ operators can't tell whether
  their last command landed without running a follow-up query. That's the next
  thing I'm shipping, with a worker running on it in the background. The
  remaining six range from missing help text to a pre-flight sanity checker that
   would have prevented the first failure case entirely. All queued, all
  sequenced, none forgotten.

  The plan from here is to work through the queue in priority order ‚ÄĒ small
  polish items first, then a design-level improvement to the delegation help,
  then the sanity checker, then correcting a minor documentation error from an
  earlier PR, then Phase 4 starts. I'll report on milestones, not individual
  items.

